[[File:Sutton Hoo lyre (reconstruction).jpg|150px|right|thumb|Reconstruction of the lyre from the Sutton Hoo ship-burial. A similar instrument was excavated at Bergh Apton.]] '''Bergh Apton Anglo-Saxon cemetery''' is a late-5th to late-6th century [[Anglo-Saxon]] burial site discovered at [[Bergh Apton]], [[Norfolk]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Aspects of Anglo-Saxon inhumation burial: Morning Thorpe, Spong Hill, Bergh Apton and Westgarth Gardens|journal=East Anglian Archaeology Reports|issue=119|year=2007|isbn=978-0-905-59445-3|publisher=Norfolk Museums and Archaeology Service|first1=Kenneth|last1=Penn|first2=Birte|last2=Brugmann|first3=Karen|last3=Høilund Nielsen|editor-first1=Brian|editor-last1=Ayers|editor-first2=Jenny|editor-last2=Glazebrook|location=Dereham}}</ref> The site was excavated in 1973 and 63 graves were found.<ref name="mlac">{{cite web|work=[[Museums, Libraries and Archives Council]]|title=Bergh Apton Anglo-Saxon cemetery collection|url=http://www.cornucopia.org.uk/html/search/verb/GetRecord/7116|accessdate=4 March 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923210545/http://www.cornucopia.org.uk/html/search/verb/GetRecord/7116|archivedate=23 September 2015|df=}}</ref> The south and west portions of the site had previously been destroyed.<ref>{{cite journal|issue=7|year=1978|title=The Anglo-Saxon Cemetery at Bergh Apton, Norfolk: Catalogue|first1=Barbara|last1=Green|first2=Andrew|last2=Rogerson|journal=East Anglian Archaeology Reports|location=Gressenhall|publisher=Norfolk Archaeological Unit|oclc=13595544}}</ref> The state of preservation of the skeletal remains was described as "very poor" due to the acidity of the soil and the sex of individuals was determined by grave goods.<ref name=mlac/><ref name="buckberry">{{cite web|first=Jo|last=Buckberry|title=Missing, Presumed Buried? Bone Diagenesis and the Under-Representation of Anglo-Saxon Children|work=Assemblage: The Sheffield Graduate Journal of Archaeology|publisher=[[University of Sheffield]]|location=Sheffield|url=http://www.assemblage.group.shef.ac.uk/5/buckberr.html|year=2000|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref><ref name="spooner">{{cite web|publisher=Norfolk Historic Environment Service|work=Norfolk Heritage Explorer|title=Parish Summary: Bergh Apton|url=http://www.heritage.norfolk.gov.uk/record-details?TNF163-Bergh-Apton-%28Parish-Summary%29|first=Sarah|last=Spooner|date=16 August 2005|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref> Grave goods found at the site included weapons, shields, spears and jewellery. One grave, possibly of a minstrel-poet, was found to contain a [[lyre]] similar to that found at [[Sutton Hoo]].<ref name=mlac/> Twelve of the graves were those of children aged under 12 years.<ref name=buckberry/> No evidence for an Anglo-Saxon settlement adjacent to the cemetery has been found.<ref name=spooner/><ref>{{cite book|title=The Archaeology of the East Anglian Conversion|first=Richard|last=Hoggett|page=120|publisher=The Boydell Press|location=Woodbridge|isbn=-978-1-843-83595-0}}</ref>
The artefacts are currently held by [[Norwich Castle|Norwich Castle Museum]].<ref name=mlac/>
